Predicting Success of Telemarketing Campaigns

Karthik Radhakrishnan

2024-12-01

Goal

Predicting success of telemarketing campaigns using 3 different models (logistic regression, LDA & random forest) and choose the best model based on predictive performance.

Analysis:

Class Separation

Duration: This variable strongly distinct between yes and no subscriptions, with clear evidence that longer call durations often lead to subscriptioins.

Other variables such as balance, day,campaign, pdays, previous doesnt show significant separation, indicating these variables may not be a strong differentiator for subscription.

Correlation analysis

pdays and previous are having moderate positive correlation. None of the other numerical variables shows significant correlation with each other.

Creating loess plots for numeric predictors

#converting response variable to numeric and store in a separate variable
bank$y.num <- ifelse(bank$y == "yes",1,0)

#loess plot for all numeric variables

for (var in numeric_vars) {
  print(
    ggplot(bank, aes(x = .data[[var]], y = y.num)) +  # Dynamically map the variable
      geom_point() + 
      geom_smooth(method = "loess", size = 1, span = 1) + 
      ylim(-0.2, 1.2) + 
      ggtitle(paste("Loess plot of", var)) +
      theme_minimal()
  )
}

Age & likelihood of subscription:

  • The LOESS curve demonstrates a U-shaped relationship between age and the likelihood of subscription. The U-shaped trend suggests that modeling approaches should consider potential non-linearity in the effect of age on subscription likelihood.
  • Younger clients and older clients (especially those above 60 years) are more likely to subscribe to term deposits compared to middle-aged clients.

Balance & likelihood of subscription:

  • The LOESS curve indicates a non-linear relationship between balance (average yearly balance) and the likelihood of subscribing to a term deposit.
  • For clients with balances greater than 30,000, the curve shows a decreasing trend in subscription likelihood.This may suggest that wealthier clients might have different investment preferences, such as stocks, bonds, or other high-return instruments, instead of term deposits.

Day & likelihood of subscription

  • The LOESS curve for day (day of the month when the client was last contacted) shows a nearly flat trend with subscription likelihood.
  • This indicates that the day of the month does not have a significant impact on whether a client subscribes to a term deposit.

Duration & likelihood of subscription

  • The LOESS curve reveals a strong positive relationship between duration (duration of the last contact in seconds) and y_num (likelihood of subscription).
  • Longer call durations are clearly associated with a higher probability of subscription.

Campaign & likelihood of subscription

  • The LOESS curve shows a slight negative trend between the number of contacts made during the campaign (campaign) and the likelihood of subscription.
  • As the number of campaign contacts increases, the likelihood of subscription decreases marginally.

pdays & likelihood of subscription - The LOESS curve indicates a positive relationship between pdays (number of days since the client was last contacted in a previous campaign) and likelihood of subscription. - As the value of pdays increases, the likelihood of subscription also increases. - The increase in subscription likelihood becomes more pronounced for values of pdays above 400 days. This suggests that clients who were contacted a long time ago (or rarely contacted) may be more receptive to the current campaign.

previous & likelihood of subscription

  • The LOESS curve shows a non-linear relationship between the number of previous contacts (previous) and the likelihood of subscription.
  • Initially, as the number of previous contacts increases, the likelihood of subscription rises.However, after reaching a peak at approximately 510 previous contacts, the likelihood starts to decline.
  • Clients who were contacted 510 times in previous campaigns are more likely to subscribe, but repeated contacts beyond this range might have a negative impact.

Feature selection for logistic regression model

library(caret)

# train and test validation split
set.seed(1234)

trainIndex<-createDataPartition(bank$y,p=.5,list=FALSE)  #p: proportion of data in train

training<-bank[trainIndex,]
validate<-bank[-trainIndex,]

# fitting a glmnet model with logloss as error metric

fitControl<-trainControl(method="repeatedcv",number=10,repeats=1,classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)

glmnet.fit <- train(
  y ~ .-y.num,
  data = training,
  method = "glmnet",
  trControl = fitControl,
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = 1, lambda = seq(0.001, 0.1, length = 10)), # Set alpha = 1
  preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
  metric = "ROC"
)

glmnet.fit

fitting a LDA Model

fitControl<-trainControl(method="repeatedcv",number=10,repeats=1,classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=mnLogLoss)

lda.fit<-train(y~age+balance+day+duration+campaign+pdays+previous,
               data=training,
               method="lda",
               trControl=fitControl,
               metric="logLoss")

#Computing predicted probabilities on the validation data using LDA model
lda.predictions <- predict(lda.fit, validate, type = "prob")[,"yes"]

Computing the AUROC for complex logistic model, knn & random forest model for comparison

library(pROC)
## Type 'citation("pROC")' for a citation.
## 
## Attaching package: 'pROC'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     cov, smooth, var
logistic.roc<-roc(response=validate$y,predictor=pred_prob,levels=c("no","yes"))
## Setting direction: controls < cases
logistic_auc <- auc(logistic.roc)
print(paste("AUC of complex logistic regression model:", round(logistic_auc, 3)))
## [1] "AUC of complex logistic regression model: 0.898"
lda.roc<-roc(response=validate$y,predictor=lda.predictions,levels=c("no","yes"))
## Setting direction: controls < cases
lda_auc <- auc(lda.roc)
print(paste("AUC of LDA model:", round(lda_auc, 3)))
## [1] "AUC of LDA model: 0.832"
# Calculate the ROC for random forest model

# Predict probabilities on the validation set
rf_probabilities <- predict(rf_model, validate, type = "prob")  # Get probabilities

# Extract probabilities for the positive class ("yes")
rf_positive_probs <- rf_probabilities[, "yes"]

# Calculate the ROC curve
rf_roc <- roc(response = validate$y, predictor = rf_positive_probs, levels = c("no", "yes"))
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Calculate and display the AUC
rf_auc <- auc(rf_roc)
print(paste("AUC of Random Forest Model:", round(rf_auc, 3)))
## [1] "AUC of Random Forest Model: 0.916"
#Plot the ROC curves for the 3 models

plot(rf_roc,print.thres="best",col="blue")
plot(lda.roc,add=T,col="red")
plot(logistic.roc,add=T,col="black")

legend("bottomright",legend=c("Random Forest","LDA","Logistc"),col=c("blue","red","black"),lwd=3,cex=1,xpd=TRUE,horiz=FALSE)

Conclusion

Random forest is the most optimal model for predicting success of telemarketing campaigns because of its ability to capture how many of the predicted subscribers actually subscribe, is better than other models.(Best positive predictive value)
